{"title_page": "Irini Tzortzoglou", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Irini Tzortzoglou\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Irini Tzortzoglou\n| birth_date   = {{bda|1960|01|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = Crete\n| years_active = 2018\u2013present\n| occupation   = Chef\n| Residence    = [[Cartmel]]\n| children     = \n| website     = [https://irinicooks.com/Official Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Irini Tzortzoglou''' is a Greek cook and winner of the [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef 2019]] UK TV show competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/masterchef|title=MasterChef 2019 Champion crowned after first ever all-female final, 29 March 2019|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHer final menu was to prepare a three-course meal for judges [[John Torode]] and [[Gregg Wallace]]. Tzortzoglou's winning menu consisted of:\n\n* ''First course: Red mullet with a squid risotto, confit tomatoes, a rosemary and garlic sauce, with bottarga (grey mullet roe) and an aged balsamic foam''\n* ''Main course: Griddled rosemary lamb chops with trahanas puree (cracked wheat cooked in soured milk), peas, confit herb tomatoes, pearl onions, crumbled feta and a lamb and tomato jus''\n* ''Dessert: Fig and hazelnut baklava with roasted honeyed fig topped with Chantilly cream and candied fig, a fig leaf ice-cream and syrup on a hazelnut crumble''\n\n\nHer first book ''Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen'' will be published on 23 July 2020.\n\n\n==Early life==\n\nTzortzoglou was born in 1960 and raised in a small village on the island of Crete, Greece. When she was 20 years old her father died prematurely and she began working in her uncle's hotel where she met her first husband who was English. She subsequently moved to London in 1980 where she got married.\n\nShe began her career in banking with the National Bank of Greece in London. Her career in banking lasted nearly thirty years and she became involved in numerous activities while also studying at Kingston University for a History of Art, Architecture and Design Degree. She married her second husband John and moved to the small village of [[Cartmel]] in [[Cumbria]] in 2010.\n\nHer Greek upbringing and family influence with food and cooking inspired her to enter [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47751390|title=MasterChef 2019 winner has no plans to open own restaurant, 30 March 2019|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n* ''Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen'' (2020) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.headline.co.uk/contributor/irini-tzortzoglou/|title=Meet the Author - Irini Tzortzoglou: Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen |website=Headline Publishing Group}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n  | before = [[Kenny Tutt]]\n  | title  = [[BBC]] [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]] champion\n  | years  = 2019\n  | after  = TBA\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://irinicooks.com/}}\n*{{twitter|irinitzo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tzortzoglou Irini}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:British chefs]]\n[[Category:Greek chefs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Crete]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Irini Tzortzoglou\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Irini Tzortzoglou\n| birth_date   = {{bda|1960|01|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = Crete\n| years_active = 2018\u2013present\n| occupation   = Chef\n| Residence    = [[Cartmel]]\n| children     = \n| website     = [https://irinicooks.com/Official Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Irini Tzortzoglou''' is an Greek cook and winner of the [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef 2019]] UK TV show competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2019/masterchef|title=MasterChef 2019 Champion crowned after first ever all-female final, 29 March 2019|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHer final menu was to prepare a three-course meal for judges [[John Torode]] and [[Gregg Wallace]]. Tzortzoglou's winning menu consisted of:\n\n* ''First course: Red mullet with a squid risotto, confit tomatoes, a rosemary and garlic sauce, with bottarga (grey mullet roe) and an aged balsamic foam''\n* ''Main course: Griddled rosemary lamb chops with trahanas puree (cracked wheat cooked in soured milk), peas, confit herb tomatoes, pearl onions, crumbled feta and a lamb and tomato jus''\n* ''Dessert: Fig and hazelnut baklava with roasted honeyed fig topped with Chantilly cream and candied fig, a fig leaf ice-cream and syrup on a hazelnut crumble''\n\n\nHer first book ''Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen'' will be published on 23 July 2020.\n\n\n==Early life==\n\nTzortzoglou was born in 1960 and raised in a small village on the island of Crete, Greece. When she was 20 years old her father died prematurely and she began working in her uncle's hotel where she met her first husband who was English. She subsequently moved to London in 1980 where she got married.\n\nShe began her career in banking with the National Bank of Greece in London. Her career in banking lasted nearly thirty years and she became involved in numerous activities while also studying at Kingston University for a History of Art, Architecture and Design Degree. She married her second husband John and moved to the small village of [[Cartmel]] in [[Cumbria]] in 2010.\n\nHer Greek upbringing and family influence with food and cooking inspired her to enter [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47751390|title=MasterChef 2019 winner has no plans to open own restaurant, 30 March 2019|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n\n* ''Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen'' (2020) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.headline.co.uk/contributor/irini-tzortzoglou/|title=Meet the Author - Irini Tzortzoglou: Under the Olive Tree: Recipes from my Greek Kitchen |website=Headline Publishing Group}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n  | before = [[Kenny Tutt]]\n  | title  = [[BBC]] [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]] champion\n  | years  = 2019\n  | after  = TBA\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|https://irinicooks.com/}}\n*{{twitter|irinitzo}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tzortzoglou Irini}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:British chefs]]\n[[Category:Greek chefs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Crete]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irini_Tzortzoglou"}
{"title_page": "Big 12 Conference football", "text_new": "The [[Big 12 Conference]] is a conference of 10 (originally 12) universities which participate in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'s [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Football Bowl Subdivision]] [[American football|football]].  The conference was formed in 1994 but did not begin conference play until the fall of 1996.  The schools that compose the Big 12 Conference, except West Virginia, were members of either the [[Big Eight Conference]] or the [[Southwest Conference]], and have won 21 [[NCAA Division I FBS National Football Championship|national titles]] including 3 titles since the inception of the Big 12 Conference.\n\n==Membership==\n\n===Current===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Institution\n!Team Name<br>(Mascot)\n!Location<br>(Population)\n!Team Started\n!Affiliation\n!Enrollment\n!Divisional Titles\n!Big 12 Titles\n!National Titles\n|-\n| [[Baylor University]]\n| [[Baylor Bears|Bears]]<br>({{nowrap|[[Judge and Bruiser (mascots)|Lady and Joy (live) and Bruiser and Marigold (costumed)]]}})\n| [[Waco, Texas]]<br>(132,356)\n| 1896\n| Private / Baptist\n| 16,959\n| 0\n| 2\n| 0\n|-\n| [[Iowa State University]]\n| [[Iowa State Cyclones|Cyclones]]<br>({{nowrap|[[Cy the Cardinal]]}})\n| [[Ames, Iowa]]<br>(65,060)\n| 1892\n| Public\n| 36,350\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| [[University of Kansas]]\n| [[Kansas Jayhawks|Jayhawks]]<br>({{nowrap|[[Big Jay (mascot)|Big Jay]]}} / {{nowrap|[[Baby Jay]]}})\n| [[Lawrence, Kansas]]<br>(93,917)\n| 1890\n| Public\n| 27,565\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n| [[Kansas State University]]\n| [[Kansas State Wildcats|Wildcats]]<br>({{nowrap|[[Willie the Wildcat (Kansas State)|Willie the Wildcat]]}})\n| [[Manhattan, Kansas]]<br>(56,308)\n| 1896\n| Public\n| 23,779\n| 4\n| 2\n| 0\n|-\n| [[University of Oklahoma]]\n| [[Oklahoma Sooners|Sooners]]<br>({{nowrap|[[Sooner Schooner]]}} / {{nowrap|[[Boomer and Sooner]]}})\n| [[Norman, Oklahoma]]<br>(120,284)\n| 1895\n| 